# Project Conventions

Stack: Next.js 14 App Router, strict TypeScript, Prisma + PostgreSQL (Supabase), Tailwind + shadcn/ui.

## TypeScript

- `strict` mode is non-negotiable. No `any`. Use `unknown` + narrowing when type is uncertain.
- Prefer explicit return types on exported functions and API handlers.
- Use Prisma-generated types for DB models; extend with Zod schemas at API boundaries.

## API Routes

Every `app/api/**/route.ts` handler MUST validate input with Zod before any business logic:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
const body = CreateBusinessSchema.parse(await request.json());

// ❌ BAD — untyped destructuring
const { name, ownerPhone } = await request.json();
```

- Return typed JSON responses; use consistent error shapes (`{ error: string, code?: string }`).
- Validate query params and route params with Zod, not manual checks.

## Environment Variables

All env vars live in a single `src/env.ts` (or `lib/env.ts`) using `@t3-oss/env-nextjs` or equivalent:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD — typed, validated at startup
export const env = createEnv({
  server: { RETELL_API_KEY: z.string().min(1), ... },
  client: { ... },
});

// ❌ BAD — scattered process.env access
const key = process.env.RETELL_API_KEY;
```

Never read `process.env` directly outside `env.ts`.

## Scope

Follow `CALLCATCH_SPEC.md` as the single source of truth. Do not add features listed under non-goals v1 without explicit approval.
